@eteq Let's say the user wants to fit `(x_0, y_0, flux, sigma)` with `IterativelySubtractedPSFPhotometry` and he/she uses `positions` (``do_photometry`` method) to provide initial guesses. But then, in the next iterations, ``IterativelySubtractedPSFPhotometry`` uses ``self.finder`` and ``aperture_photometry`` to set up initial guesses for `(x_0, y_0)` and ``flux`` of fainter sources, respectively. However, there's no direct way to set up initial guesses for ``sigma`` (or any other parameter) in the next iterations. The solution right now is just to take the default value in the `psf_model`, i.e., `psf_model.sigma.value`, as the initial guess. 
For the case of ``sigma``, this is relatively good assuming that true value of ``sigma`` does not deviate much across the image.

But to provide a complete solution to this, I think maybe we should allow the user to pass callables to ``IterativelySubtractedPSFPhotometry`` which would be used to compute initial guesses for any additional parameters for iterations `n > 1`.

@bsandrow: The `type` is part of the JSON response itself. When you catch the error in Python, you access the details directly in `json_body` which is where the type is. It doesn't need to be defined in the error class itself and just parsed dynamically.

