The new behavior will be that the parser will accept string types (`unicode`, `str` in Python 2.x or `str` and `bytes` in Python 3.x) or any object that implements the `read()` interface and returns characters. Passing anything else to the parser will raise a `TypeError`.

I don't think it makes sense to return a datetime if passed a datetime, since the point of the parser is to pass it a string, and it's probably not a good idea to just silently do nothing. End users can implement a wrapper around the parser that takes strings or datetimes if they want.

